{
  "texts": [
    "(5.61)We do not expect any further infrared divergence at this order, in particular no real divergences, since the inclusive waveform should not be suppressed by the small \"probability to not radiate\" that is familiar for exclusive processes.",
    "The prediction (5.61) is supported nontrivially in appendix B where we compute the soft function for Wilson lines that follow the appropriate JHEP01(2024)139Many generalized amplitudes compute interesting observables with standard names, such as inclusive production cross-sections and inclusive waveforms, or, more exotically, out-of-time-order correlators in a scattering background, as discussed in section 2.2.",
    "Many observables usually thought of as quadratic in the S-matrix are simply linear in generalized amplitudes.",
    "We anticipate that this unified viewpoint will facilitate the application of amplitude techniques to the computation of these more general observables, or even inspire the discovery of new ones.",
    "The choice of operator ordering can have dramatic physical effects, such as changing the size of the amplitude from being exponentially small to being entirely unsuppressed."
  ]
}